1 Summer, 2023 ARTICLE & COMMENT: THE MEME STOCK BIDDING WAR VIEWED FROM THE LENSES OF THE AMERICAN AND CANADIAN SECURITIES REGULATORS [*194] I. INTRODUCTION Online trading has significantly increased during the past several years due in large part to the pandemic and federal paychecks.2 Mobile apps and social media paved the way for laypeople to engage in securities shopping and make easy money while resting at home or attending their mandatory zoom meetings.3 Investors from various backgrounds and financial capabilities were given a commission-free access to the financial market.4 Such fool-proof access meant a jackpot for some, but the kiss of death for others. The United States ("U.S.") and Canadian markets have witnessed extreme price volatility in the stocks' trading prices of the notorious GameStop Corporation ("GME") and AMC Entertainment Holdings, Inc. ("AMC").5 The wild swing was mainly caused by a bidding war between investors who were engaged in some sort of gambling.6 The tables have turned and everyday retail investors won a long-lost war against powerful financial institutions. This phenomenon has been called the meme stock saga.7 Individual investors are frequently mocked on Wall Street as "dumb money," doomed to lose to the highly compensated analysts and traders who [*195] purchase and sell stocks for a livelihood.8 Individual investors, many of whom are fans of the popular Reddit page, "WallStreetBets," have teamed together to put the squeeze on at least two hedge funds that bet on GameStop's stock falling.9 The stock's record surge coincided with better access to options bets than ever before, allowing investors to increase their bullish bets, and in certain cases, inflicting further misery on short sellers.10 Bubbles, like GameStop, hurt the market as a whole.11 When they ultimately burst, not only will the speculators suffer the consequences, but also, other market actors, retirees and publicly traded companies who rely on it will suffer as well.12 The Honorable Frank Iacobucci Puisne Justice of the Supreme Court of Canada13 wrote, "in considering an order in the public interest, it is an error to focus only on the fair treatment of investors. The effect of an intervention in the public interest on capital market efficiencies and public confidence in the capital markets should also be considered."14 This judicial request for regulators to consider a variety of purposes when acting as gatekeepers is correct. Even though the U.S. and Canadian securities regulators were expected to protect retail investors from themselves during the GameStop frenzy, those investors were the ones lighting the fire that could potentially burn other market actors.15 For instance, third party creditors lending money to GME and AMC risked extending loans for cheaper prices as these companies' stocks were constantly fluctuating.16 Markets work on the idea that creditors can actually negotiate value on the underlying basis that they understand the value of a company.17 GME and AMC would suddenly have an inflated value and get different types of loans at a much cheaper price. [*196] However, once the value of the stocks drops down and gets back to normal, third-party creditors, who relied on specific ratings, get stuck with an interest rate that should have never been determined.18 It is worth mentioning here that investors are behind this price fluctuation, not GME or AMC.19 The protections afforded to those creditors in light of this temporary inflation is beyond this Note; however, this mania is dangerous to the financial market as a whole, not just for investors. Dynamism and innovation, for the most part, help the economy as a whole and investors in particular.20 That same energy and creativity, on the other hand, may and does lead to misuse.21 A regulatory agency in charge of monitoring capital markets must be able to act rapidly to block transactions that it considers to be harmful to the capital markets.22 The same phenomenon was observed in Canada as GME and AMC stocks were traded there as well.23 Unlike the Securities and Exchange Commission ("SEC"), the Ontario Securities Commission ("OSC") possesses a unique tool in their arsenal known as "public interest jurisdiction," which empowers securities regulators to intervene in certain circumstances.24 More precisely, OSC has the authority to issue orders on anything that, in its judgment, is in the public interest, even if no specific securities law violation has occurred.25 Nonetheless, this power has been reserved for conduct that rises to the level of "abus[e]" of investors or the capital markets.26 This Article will provide a general overview of the events that led to the meme stock frenzy and the reaction of the U.S. and Canadian governments to the extreme volatility of the GME and AMC stocks. This Article will also analyze the various definitions of market manipulation adopted in both countries. More specifically, it will explore the OSC's public interest jurisdiction and its effectiveness even absent a violation of the Ontario Securities Act ("Act"). Part I focuses on the role of social media in bumping the meme stock value, creating the short squeeze, and leading to the gamification of trading. Part II discusses the inaction of the American and Canadian lawmakers amidst the exceptional price fluctuation of the stocks. Part III profiles numerous cases of market manipulation and explores the evolution of the OSC's public interest jurisdiction, initially intended as a precautionary measure but ultimately resulting in punitive measures. Part IV [*197] analyzes the meme stock saga under the current laws of both countries and discusses why the OSC could have intervened even if the Act was not violated. Finally, Section V concludes that neither legal system was designed to apply to this unprecedented frenzy. II. BACKGROUNDA. The Meme Stock Saga in a Nutshell1. How it all Started: a Screen Shot on WallStreetBets An unusual bidding war in shares of companies that were once underwater has wreaked havoc upon Wall Street's ecosystem and left the SEC's hands tied since January 2021. While the general public was ecstatic about their newfound wealth, professionals were in shock as a result of their losses.27 Hedge fund investors, who have lost billions, were defeated by individual investors who mocked them on social media.28 The turn of events has raised regulatory and legal issues and attracted the attention of President Biden's administration.29 Inexperienced investors congregated on platforms such as Reddit, Discord, Facebook, and Twitter.30 Professional traders complained that social media swarms were conspiring to move stock prices, and they were encouraging each other to pile into stocks, bragging about their gains, and on occasion, intentionally banding together to intensify losses among professional traders, who claimed that social media users were conspiring to influence stock prices.31 Since early January 2021, GameStop and AMC have garnered numerous mentions on social media, propelling them into the most traded stocks category in the U.S.32 Money managers have been compelled to dump [*198] bets on the stock market fall, exacerbating the boom.33 According to financial analytics firm S3 Partners, bearish investors who took short positions on GameStop have lost $ 23.6 billion early January 2021 through the close of trading on January 27, 2021, including $ 14.3 billion when the stock price jumped 135%, the largest percentage increase in history, to a record $ 347.51.34 Speculative options trading on GameStop and AMC has reached an all-time high, leaving traders enthralled by the price swings on their screens.35 It is hard to pinpoint the start of the GameStop frenzy, but signals of individual investor interest began to appear in earnest on Reddit boards in 2019.36 Some individuals posted photos of optimistic options positions and debated why the stock would climb at the moment.37 Known as "4chan found a Bloomberg terminal," the Reddit forum, WallStreetBets has become overwhelmingly popular in the past few years as the number of subscribers has jumped from approximately 500,000 in the 2010-2018 period to 11,526,704 subscribers in 2021.38 Keith Gill, also known as Roaring Kitty on the Reddit forum, posted a screenshot on the forum WallStreetBets showing his $ 53,000 investment in GME stock in September 2019.39 Mr. Gill said he began investing in GameStop in June of 2019, when the stock was hovering at about $ 5 a share.40 He relied heavily on Twitter and YouTube to promote GME stock and attract the attention of young investors.41 In 2020, he posted about his investments on Twitter, YouTube, and TikTok.42 He became the inspiration for some [*199] individual investors, especially young online traders, who liked the idea of competing against sophisticated hedge funds.43 What pushed up GameStop's price was the excessive buying of the options contracts through no-fee online trading platforms like Robinhood and Webull.44 Keith Gill and his fans showed commitment for GameStop investment by discussing the company's financial filings and cryptic details about free-cash flow and video game consoles in the comments section of Mr. Gill's videos on Reddit.45 GameStop had gone from a stock suggestion to a spectacle by early January 2021.46 GameStop was no longer just a way to make a big profit or invest in a struggling firm, but also purchasing GameStop had become a strategy to combat institutional money.47 "Do not sell," said one user, encouraging others to do the same and to continue to cripple the hedge funds.48 Hedge funds and other financial experts poured into bets that the stock would fall.49 Because there were more shares short than outstanding, hedge funds became overly invested in GameStop.50 But the scenario did not go as they expected it to play out.51 This time, individual investors banded together to drive the stock higher, pushing hedge funds to buy back shares and cover their short positions, which in turn drove the price even higher.52 2. GameStop Short Squeeze: The Wall Street Karma By 2020, speculation about a possible short squeeze had moved beyond a hunch among a few users.53 In posts during the first quarter of 2020, there was a surge in short interest in GameStop stock, with one user predicting the "biggest short squeeze of your entire life" in April 2020.54 "Shorting" to [*200] begin with, is an investment strategy involving some type of gambling by short sellers.55 These sellers borrow shares from brokers and then sell them in the market with the promise of buying them back and returning them to the lender at a later date.56 The shares can come from the brokers' own stockpiles or from customers who have given their permission for the brokers to lend out their stock.57 It is a particularly hazardous strategy because, while a stock's price cannot fall more than 100%, it can go up indefinitely, potentially incurring infinite losses.58 If the time comes to return the shares and the stock price has dropped, the short seller can buy them back at a cheaper price than when they were first purchased, ensuring a profit.59 If the price rises, the short seller will have to buy the shares back at the higher price, resulting in a loss.60 Meanwhile, the short seller pays the loan interest on the stock's value, providing the lender with extra income.61 GME shares were over 100% shorted before the GME surge, "implying that more shares were shorted than were available to trade."62 Because the settlement of a short stock sale takes two days to complete, the stock can be leased out many times.63 This allows a stock to be shorted in excess of 100%.64 According to financial analytics firm S3, GameStop's highest short interest was 141.8% of its entire shares available for trade.65 [*201] In January 2021, GameStop's demise had been significantly bet on by huge institutional investors.66 They borrowed shares and sold them in the hopes of repurchasing them at a lower price later and pocketing the difference.67 Yet, GameStop's stock price soared from under $ 20 in early January to nearly $ 500 by January 28th an increase of well over 1,000% for no discernible reason other than the efforts of thousands of internet message board users to force a "short squeeze" targeting asset managers who had shorted the stock in anticipation of the expected declines of GameStop's stock price based on their analysis of the company's financial statements.68 For instance, the top-performing hedge fund, Melvin Capital Management, which controlled $ 12.5 billion at the start of the year, had lost about 30% for the year through the end of January, owing mostly to its array of wagers against companies such as GameStop.69 The GME frenzy resulted [*202] in a bidding war between different types of investors with conflicting goals.70 Institutional players, hedge funds, and investment experts lined up on one side and retail investors, online traders, and tiny brokerages lined up on the other.71 3. The Gamification of Trading GameStop Options on Robinhood App Retail traders did not simply buy and sell stocks during the meme stock frenzy, they also purchased and sold options, which are a type of financial instrument that grants the holder the right to buy or sell a stock.72 Investors who purchase options have the choice to acquire or sell shares at particular prices at a later date.73 They can be used as trading tools to speculate on stock direction or as a hedge for portfolios.74 Thus, many investors have utilized them recently to double, triple, or even quadruple their money, because they may put down a modest amount in exchange for a large return.75 However, this all comes with the risk of a large loss.76 Small investors were buying GME options that would expire in a few of days.77 After a record-breaking year in 2020, options volumes skyrocketed in 2021.78 According to Trade Alert data, the first three weeks of 2021 saw four of the five highest volume days for call options since 1973.79 On January 27, 2021, over 39 million bullish calls were traded, making it the most active day in the history of such bets.80 Wall Street veterans were shocked as the options volumes for GameStop and AMC escalated.81 Because options are more profitable, brokerage firms have extensively promoted them to retail investors.82 Robinhood claimed that it "democratized" trading by making financial markets accessible to everyone.83 Retail investors who traded through the app paid no commissions.84 Brokerages such as Charles Schwab, TD Ameritrade, and E-Trade previously [*203] imposed fees to trade equities on their platforms.85 These large brokerages were forced to adapt because they realized they would lose consumers if they charged $ 6.95 each trade while Robinhood was free.86 As the world economy crumbled under the weight of the Coronavirus outbreak, millions of novice investors armed with $ 1,200 stimulus checks started trading via Robinhood.87 Robinhood added over three million accounts in the first eight months of 2020.88 The company's sales increased by 250% from the previous year.89 Robinhood changed its commission system, and it was gaining market influence.90 The trading volume at Robinhood increased by 139% from the first quarter of 2020, considerably outperforming its competitors E-Trade and Charles Schwab.91 Even though Robinhood eliminated trade commissions, it made $ 271 million selling "payment for order flow" ("PFOF") in the first half of 2020.92 Technically, the money came from selling its customers' trading orders to large investment firms, who then employ computer algorithms to buy and sell the equities Robinhood members are trading.93 The spread between the bid and offer prices is how these companies make money.94 Therefore, the more the price fluctuates, the more money Robinhood makes. Eventually, Citadel Securities and other companies pay Robinhood to funnel customer orders to them, which is normal practice among retail brokerages.95 Citadel generates money by exploiting minute price variations to purchase and sell utilizing its high-speed trading engines.96 These are frequently fractions of pennies, but with the large number of trades Citadel makes, it quickly adds up.97 As a risk management decision, Robinhood chose to temporarily limit certain types of trading in approximately fifty different securities, including GameStop.98 Robinhood claimed this was necessary to protect the platform [*204] and its clearinghouses, as well as to ensure compliance with various regulatory requirements.99 The halt of trading in the midst of the GME spike was not well-liked by retail investors and politicians.100 Some accused Robinhood to be more on the side of the institutional firms to which it sells its PFOFs, such as Citadel, as compared to retail investors.101 Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez called the GME trading halt "unacceptable" and urged a probe.102 Senator Ted Cruz took to Twitter to "[f]ully agree" with her.103 Elon Musk replied, "[a]bsolutely"104 and called for short selling to be banned as "a scam."105 On January 28th, an investor filed a putative class action lawsuit against Robinhood in the United States Southern District of New York, alleging that trading restrictions implemented during the volatility had "deprived retail investors of the ability to invest in the open-market . . ." with the intent "to manipulate the market for the benefit of . . . financial intuitions."106 Almost a dozen other lawsuits against Robinhood and others were filed in state and federal courts around the country shortly thereafter.107 Others argued that Robinhood suspended trades to escape potential [*205] SEC wrath and elude regulatory inspection given the site's explosive growth during the Coronavirus pandemic.108 The risk of exorbitant fines if clients engage in manipulative behavior keeps brokers' eyes wide open.109 Unlike social media sites, which are shielded from accountability for malicious users, online brokerage platforms are subject to the exact opposite laws.110 Firms must perform reasonable surveillance for client fraud or crime under federal anti-money laundering legislation.111 The SEC and other regulators have fined banks and brokers (including E-Trade, Interactive Brokers, and Charles Schwab) hundreds of millions of dollars in recent years due to their failure to detect and prevent customer wrongdoing.112 While the legal standard appears to be negligence ("reasonable surveillance"), regulators frequently utilize 20/20 hindsight to dispute broker due diligence of their customers after the fact, imposing severe liability.113 Customers do not need to be found guilty of manipulation in order for the broker to be penalized since a behavior that is "potentially" suspicious is enough to land the broker in hot water.114 Robinhood and other retail trading firms blamed "extreme volatility" and refused to trade.115 They restricted customers from buying GME stock and only allowed customers to sell their existing positions.116 Robinhood's CEO Vlad Tenev refuted that Robinhood was experiencing a liquidity problem, explaining that "'[l]iquidity issue' means you can't meet your capital requirements or your deposit requirements, and you're essentially dead. That was not the case with Robinhood."117 To meet loan criteria from the country's central "clearing facility" for stock trading, the Depository Trust & Clearing Corporation, Robinhood was compelled to borrow between $ 500 and $ 600 million.118 Robinhood failed to meet a $ 3 billion collateral request [*206] from the clearinghouse on January 28, 2021.119 The $ 3 billion bill was cut by approximately 75% by ceasing trade, which Robinhood could afford to raise from investors and pay up front.120 Robinhood's position, regardless of its accuracy, is not unsubstantiated. Whether or not clients can pay for their lost trades, brokers are financially obligated to the clearinghouses that clear and settle U.S. stocks and options so that those clearinghouses can pay the winners on the other side when the trade settles one or two days later.121 Clients gamble with the broker's money when they trade, especially on margin.122 Consider a client who spends $ 20,000 of his own money and borrows $ 20,000 from Robinhood to buy 100 shares of GameStop for $ 400 each.123 Due to the margin breach, if the stock decreases from $ 400 to $ 120, as it did on January 28, 2021, the client's investment may be sold for $ 12,000, leaving Robinhood with an unsecured $ 8,000 debt.124 Multiply this by hundreds or thousands of other clients in a similar situation.125 Robinhood's fear could be rational as trading options is riskier because the leverage is significantly higher.126 Brokers must meet stringent financial standards, including maintaining significant security deposits at clearinghouses.127 Clearinghouses enhance their criteria when risk rises, even intraday.128 When GameStop plunged from $ 483 to $ 112 on January 28th, the clearinghouse DTCC increased its requirements by $ 7.5 billion.129 Whether or not their clients had [*207] the money, brokers were required to post it to DTCC.130 Thus, when faced with a liquidity shortage, brokers could raise capital, similarly to Robinhood, or decrease their clients' riskier trading. It is unlikely that Robinhood halted GME stock trading in order to protect hedge funds. It is more likely that they were avoiding bankruptcy which is probable during market events like this.131 Trading in GME was also suspended by other brokerages, such as Charles Schwab, TD Ameritrade, and Webull.132 III. LACK OF INTERFERENCE BY LAWMAKERS AND REGULATORSA. In The U.S.1. SEC The SEC's main mission is to protect investors, maintain fair, orderly, and efficient markets, and enable capital formation.133 Amongst the wide variety of tools at its disposal, the SEC may suspend trading in a security for up to ten days, either outright or with respect to particular types of trading.134 A halt in trading would normally occur due to a lack of accurate and adequate information about the company, suspicions about the accuracy of the company's publicly available information, operational status, and financial condition, or questions about trading in the stock, including trading by insiders, potential market manipulation, and the ability to clear and settle transactions in the stock.135 For instance, amid the 2008 financial crisis, the SEC restricted short selling to maintain the market's integrity.136 Moreover, self-regulatory organizations ("SROs"), such as stock exchanges, can also halt trades in situations involving considerable imbalance in the volume of buy and sell orders in securities.137 The SEC said they "will act to protect retail investors when the facts demonstrate abusive or manipulative trading activity that is prohibited by federal securities laws."138 Nevertheless, neither the SEC nor the numerous [*208] SROs managing GameStop and other stocks with comparable patterns of excessive volatility trading disconnected from their financial fundamentals have opted to exercise this power.139 In fact, the SEC suspended trading of 101 stocks, except GameStop.140 However, it did "closely monitor[] and evaluat[e] the extreme price volatility . . ." of GameStop.141 The SEC's Office of Investor Education and Advocacy also warned investors of the significant risks of short-term social media investment, particularly in volatile markets, and offered long-term investing advice.142 According to reports, the SEC considered increasing the transparency of short selling and the processes that go along with it.143 Despite the Dodd-Frank Act's intention to enhance transparency in the practice, the SEC did not succeed in implementing heightened regulation on short-selling as required over a decade ago.144 House lawmakers noted in a memorandum that the SEC had not completed its responsibilities under the Dodd-Frank mandate.145 Greater transparency into short sellers, according to some SEC officials, may aggravate the trading environment as others replicate the shorts, raising borrowing costs for all short sellers.146 Short sales are viewed by some as a check on stock prices, keeping them at fair value; when a stock is overvalued, short sellers attack it.147 SEC Chairman Gary Gensler said the agency was considering imposing new restrictions on brokerage apps that use technology to encourage people to trade more stocks and other securities.148 In August 2021, the SEC issued a request for public comment on broker-dealer and investment adviser digital engagement practices, as well as investment adviser use of technological information to provide investment advice.149 However, the [*209] report the SEC released in October shows its skepticism towards new stock-trading apps "that are likely intended to create positive feedback from trading lead investors to trade more than they would otherwise."150 The SEC seems to be heading towards increasing the transparency of short selling as it found that "[i]mproved reporting of short sales would allow regulators to better track these [market] dynamics."151 2. Congress Congresswoman Maxine Waters (D-CA), Chairwoman of the House Committee on Financial Services, called for a hearing to address the gamification of trades and "deal with hedge funds whose unethical conduct directly led to the recent market volatility . . . ."152 The major concern was to address questions raised by the short squeeze about the effectiveness of anti-market manipulation legislation, as well as whether technology and social media have outrun regulation, exposing investors and markets to unwarranted dangers.153 The House Financial Services Committee convened on February 18, 2021, to discuss the GameStop saga.154 Even though lawmakers expressed a variety of viewpoints on the consequences of the GameStop trading frenzy that erupted on message boards, both Republican and Democratic lawmakers targeted Robinhood.155 They also emphasized that short selling should be regulated to safeguard smaller players.156 Nevertheless, Republicans on the committee emphasized that this was not a basis for further retail investor regulation.157 Following that, on March 9, 2021, the Senate Banking Committee held a hearing.158 Pat Toomey (R-PA) supported the gamification of online stock trading as it paves the way for a person of modest means to invest in the stock market at zero or minimal cost.159 During the hearing, Payment of Order [*210] Flow ("PFOF") was chastised, but its abolition would undoubtedly spell the end of zero-commission trading.160 B. In Canada "The old rules for market professionals and regulator oversight of markets now [do not] work since these new traders are outside this ambit, . . ." according to former chair of the Ontario Securities Commission, Maureen Jensen.161 "There is no closed market system anymore and that means we have to rethink the system."162 The Canadian Securities Administrators ("CSA") and the Investment Industry Regulatory Organization of Canada ("IIROC") said they were closely monitoring the situation and pledged to take "appropriate regulatory action to protect investors . . ." if "abusive or manipulative trading activity . . ." was found.163 The statement also noted that the CSA and IIROC were in close contact with international regulators, "recognizing that trading and market volatility is not confined by borders."164 Canadian regulators were closely watching any steps the SEC would take.165 Just like their sister securities regulators in the U.S., the CSA and IIROC abstained from taking any action regarding the meme stock saga.166 Some believed that regulatory intervention might have had a negative impact on already volatile markets at this stage in Canada.167 If regulators were to go after anyone in this context, it would not be practical to go after retail traders.168 Others said that neither investors nor the trading platforms appear to be doing anything illegal or wrong, but they are taking big risks, and some of them do not even realize it.169 [*211] IV. WHAT IS MARKET MANIPULATION?A. Pump and Dump Scheme in the U.S. Questions about possible fraudulent behavior in the GME price spike developed in the aftermath of the GME jump.170 The SEC report says, "some in the media directly linked trading activity to the presence of short interest, characterizing trading in GameStop as an act of rebellion intended to humble short-selling professional investors who had allegedly targeted the stock."171 Questions arose around possible fraudulent behavior involved in GME's price spike.172 Former SEC Chairman Jay Clayton said GME's rapid rise was not the result of a social media-based pump-and-dump scheme since "[p]eople were very transparent about what they were doing and why they were doing it, which was fairly interesting."173 But when asked to demonstrate how social media posts about GameStop were different than historic pump-and-dump schemes, such as was depicted in the movie "The Wolf of Wall Street,"174 Mr. Clayton responded: I think in the abstract, you make a good argument that it's not different in that a group of people decide that they like this [same stock]. Whether they got all together and did it together like the Stratton Oakmont did, knowing the end game here, I don't think so.175 According to the SEC, market manipulation, commonly known as a pump-and-dump scheme, occurs when investors circulate misleading information to create a "buying frenzy."176 This artificially increased trading volume has the consequence of artificially inflating the price of the targeted security (the "pump"), which is quickly sold off by the fraudsters into the inflated market (the "dump").177 The stock price usually decreases after the perpetrators sell their shares and stop advertising the stock, which will make investors lose money.178 The SEC acknowledges that false or misleading information might be spread through social media and internet chat rooms.179 [*212] It has also warned investors in 2014 that those pumping the stock price could be company insiders or paid promoters who stand to profit by selling their shares after the stock is pumped higher due to their action.180 Although many newsletters are legitimate, they can be used to promote and boost stock values.181 The SEC specifically advises investors to look for a lack of or ambiguous disclosure in a newsletter as a clue that it may be fraudulent.182 15 U.S.C. [Seconds] 78j(b) prohibits any person from using or employing "in connection with the purchase or sale of any security . . . any manipulative or deceptive device or contrivance in contravention of such rules and regulations as the Commission may prescribe as necessary or appropriate in the public interest or for the protection of investors."183 In March 2019, the Supreme Court of the United States expanded the scope of Section 10(b) in Lorenzo v. SEC to include a broader class of market manipulators who were previously exempt from liability.184 Private plaintiffs and the SEC can rely on this decision to bring Section 10(b) claims against market participants who knowingly or recklessly transmit false and misleading statements that were made by someone else.185 If investors are "lying, cheating, or stealing" in connection with a stock trade, the SEC will take action.186 However, when the speech does not amount to fraud, the SEC can only advise people to do extensive research before buying instead of picking stocks at random.187 "You can buy a stock for whatever reason you want . . . except you can't buy a stock as part of a scheme to artificially distort the market for a security," said John Reed Stark, former SEC investigator.188 Moreover, 15 U.S.C. [Seconds] 78i(a) makes it unlawful for any person, directly or indirectly, by the use of the mail or any means or instrumentality of interstate commerce, or of any facility of any national securities exchange, to create a false or misleading appearance in active trading in any security and [*213] prohibits the purchase of such security with the knowledge that any order of substantially the same size, same time, and same price, for the sale of any such security has been will be entered by or for the same or different parties.189 The prohibition also extends to "effect[ing] . . . a series of transactions in any security . . . creating actual or apparent active trading in such security, or raising or depressing the price of such security[,] for the purpose of inducing the purchase or sale of such security by others."190 Potential litigation against GME traders could be based on SEC Regulation 17 C.F.R. [Seconds] 240.10b-5 ("Rule 10b-5") which makes it unlawful "[t]o employ any device, scheme, or artifice to defraud, . . . make any untrue statement of a material fact . . . in connection with the purchase or sale of any security."191 Litigants will rely more heavily on Rule 10b-5 than 15 U.S.C. [Seconds] 78i(a) of the SEC Act when making a manipulation claim as it hits the nail on the head by prohibiting pump-and-dump schemes. B. In Canada1. Proof of intent In Canada, when GameStop had its shares rise about 20-fold in just weeks, some have referred to the extraordinary rise in value as proof of manipulation, while others cautioned that drawing a boundary is difficult.192 Despite repeated appeals for authorities to intervene and prohibit short-selling, Canadian regulators have rarely done so.193 Investors have the right to their opinions in both circumstances, and regulators must show that they are attempting to manipulate the market..194 If authorities pursued this as a market manipulation case, they would have to show that the goal was to manipulate the supply, demand, or price of securities artificially.195 Securities lawyers and regulators said such prosecutions have a notoriously high bar of proof.196 Investors are expressly forbidden from engaging in or participating in transactions connected to a securities trade, whether directly or indirectly, if the investor knows, or should reasonably know, that the transaction would result in or contribute "to a misleading appearance of trading activity in, or an artificial price for, a security or a derivative of that security" under Part 3 of National Instrument 23-101.197 The same prohibition is found in the [*214] Securities Acts of British Columbia,198 Alberta,199 Ontario,200 Saskatchewan,201 and the Securities Act202 and the Derivatives203 Act of Quebec. Under Section 126.1(1)(a) of the Securities Acts of Ontario, a person or company may be held accountable even if they had no intention of inducing an artificial pricing or creating a false appearance of trading activity.204 The threshold for market manipulation is met when the person or company "reasonably ought to know" that the conduct falls into one of the two categories in paragraph (a).205 Securities legislation across Canada distinguish between "artificial price" and "misleading appearance of trading activity."206 For instance, in Re Podorieszach, the Alberta Securities Commission ("ASC") explained that an "artificial price" is a price that differs from the price that would result from the market operating freely and fairly on the basis of information concerning true market supply and demand . . . [n]ormal-course transactions between buyers and sellers, operating at arm's length, reflect real demand and supply; whatever the effect on price, it can be said to be a genuine market effect. If, however, demand or supply is distorted, then price will likely also be distorted no longer reflective of real market demand and supply, it will be artificial.207 With respect to the meaning of "misleading appearance of trading activity," it relates more to the bona fides of trading.208 It may or may not be directed at creating an artificial price.209 The motivation behind the transaction is often the focus of decisions dealing with "misleading appearance of trading activity."210 "Spoofing," for instance, could be defined as a pattern of behavior that results in a misleading appearance of trading [*215] activity.211 The OSC qualified the use of non-bona fide direct electronic access ("DEA") orders placed, and simultaneously cancelled before they could be filled, by a Toronto based manager of two private funds to increase or decrease the National Best Bid Offer ("NBBO") as spoofing.212 Those funds gained an unfair advantage over law-abiding market players by injecting misleading information into the market, stifling competition and jeopardizing the integrity of Ontario's capital markets.213 Another facet of market manipulation which falls under the umbrella of both, misleading appearance of trading activity and artificial price, is so-called "wash trading."214 A "wash trade" occurs when the buyer and seller are the same person.215 Despite the fact that it appears to be a normal purchase-and-sale transaction, the ultimate ownership has not changed--the apparent deal is really a mirage.216 Such deceptive practice creates a false impression of the consummation of actual transactions which gives rise to the false appearance of market liquidity and generate artificial prices.217 Similarly to the U.S., a "pump and dump" scheme is a common example of market manipulation, which often involves non-bona fide trading aimed at artificially inflating the price of the underlying stocks.218 In Re Kilimanjaro Capital Ltd., the ASC found the legal counsel, and allegedly, the chief operating officer of a Belizean company liable for market manipulating conduct intended to artificially inflate the company's share price for personal gain.219 Ashmit Patel, chief operating officer of Kilimanjaro Capital Ltd. ("Kilimanjaro Canada"), approached Zulfikar Rashid, chief executive officer of Kilimanjaro Canada about establishing a shell company for a project in Africa including contingent oil, gas, and mineral rights ("FCAs").220 Rashid chose to use his own company, Kilimanjaro Canada , as he could not locate an interested investor group.221 Kilimanjaro Canada issued multiple news releases shortly after Patel and Rashid struck an agreement, referring to Kilimanjaro Canada's acquisition of FCAs from several exiled African governments (the "2012 News Releases").222 The FCAs were conditional on the countries' ability to exercise self-determination.223 Kilimanjaro Canada [*216] was acquired by Kilimanjaro in March 2013.224 Kilimanjaro took joint responsibility for all of Kilimanjaro Canada's contracts at that point.225 Kilimanjaro's shares were listed on GXG Markets ("GXG"), a Danish-regulated microcap stock market, on August 29, 2013.226 Kilimanjaro's shares were traded on the Over-the-Counter ("OTC") market beginning in or around October of 2013.227 Rashid dissolved Kilimanjaro Canada in November of 2013.228 Kilimanjaro issued a number of press announcements in 2014 about its existing partnerships with exiled governments and other "developing interests," including a letter of intent to purchase some oil and gas properties in Alberta (the "2014 News Releases").229 However, neither Kilimanjaro nor Kilimanjaro Canada ever received any of the rights or assets mentioned in the 2012 or 2014 News Releases.230 Despite the fact that Rashid claimed to be Kilimanjaro's CEO, the ASC determined that Patel, not Rashid, was the organization's driving force.231 The ASC found Patel's behavior to have all of the hallmarks of a classic pump-and-dump scheme in violation of Section 93(a) of the Alberta Securities Act: secret control over the issuer and a large block of its shares, direction of a promotion replete with falsehoods and exaggerations (the pump), and simultaneous liquidation of shares (the dump), all while avoiding securities laws governing control distributions and resale through the use of phony legal opinions and third-party brokerage accounts.232 2. Public Interest Jurisdiction Unlike the SEC, Canadian regulators retain a unique tool in their hands known as the "public interest jurisdiction," which empowers them to use regulatory intervention to cope with recent market activity.233 It has been on the books since the 1960s and gives provincial securities regulators like the OSC the authority to issue orders related to matters deemed to be in the public interest according to their own judgment, even if there is no particular violation of securities legislation.234 This offers Canadian regulators a [*217] broader authority than their American peers. The broad wording of the provision has allowed for considerable discretion and interpretation in its application, resulting in varying uses of the power.235 The scope of directives that securities regulators can issue under the public interest jurisdiction has expanded significantly over time.236 At first, securities regulators could only use this power to issue cease trade orders and denials of exemptions.237 The orders are now more prevalent as they extend to disgorgement and a monetary administrative penalty, among other things.238 In 1994, the Act's formerly separate "public interest" provisions were merged into Section 127, which became its own, stand-alone basis for punishing market participants as long as the Commission deemed it in the public interest to do so.239 Despite the fact that the legislature has never defined "public interest" in the Act, the 1994 amendments described the Act's purposes in Section 1.1 as "to provide protection to investors from unfair, improper or fraudulent practices; and to foster fair and efficient capital markets and confidence in capital markets."240 Timely and accurate disclosure of information, the restrictions on fraudulent and unfair market practices and procedures, and the requirements for the maintenance or high standards or fitness and business conduct to ensure honest and responsible conduct by market participants, are among the "basic principles" that the OSC must consider when pursuing the Act's goals.241 The OSC has the authority under Section 127 of the Act to impose a wide range of sanctions on market participants when it is in the public interest to do so.242 The Supreme Court of Canada has confirmed on several occasions that the OSC's public interest jurisdiction can be exercised even when no securities laws have been breached.243 Indeed, the OSC's staff has failed to prove a violation of the Act on several occasions, yet has still prevailed based on the less stringent and broad "contrary to the public interest" threshold, in connection to the same lawful action.244 The use and scope of the public interest power are set forth in [*218] Asbestos, the leading decision of the Supreme Court of Canada.245 The facts in this case, like many others under Section 127, focused on an attempt by a group of minority shareholders to challenge the sale of Asbestos Corporation ("Asbestos Corp.") to a Quebec government-owned Crown corporation.246 The Commission had to decide whether it should interfere on "public interest" grounds, notwithstanding the fact that no violation of the Act had been established.247 The Commission declined to use its public-interest authority to halt the transaction or impose sanctions on the Quebec government.248 The Supreme Court used the occasion to comment on the right scope of the public interest power in supporting the Commission's decision.249 While Section l27 gives the Commission broad latitude to intervene in Ontario capital markets, the court held that this discretion is not infinite.250 The court noted that the "OSC should consider the protection of investors and the efficiency of, and public confidence in, capital markets generally."251 The court also emphasized that because Section 127 is a regulatory provision, "[t]he sanctions under the section are preventative in nature and prospective in orientation."252 In Cartaway, the Supreme Court of Canada reconsidered the scope of the public interest jurisdiction, however this time in connection to the British Columbia Securities Act (the "B.C. Act").253 In that instance, the Supreme Court upheld an appeal from the British Columbia Court of Appeal, and reimposed sanctions on two brokers under Section 162 of the B.C. Act (the B.C. counterpart of Section 127) for breaching the B.C. Act by failing to disclose material information and material changes in a timely manner.254 In deciding whether to make orders in the public interest, the court decided that "general deterrence" is a relevant factor to examine.255 According to the court, deterrent penalties may "target the individual wrongdoer in an attempt to show the unprofitability of repeated wrongdoing."256 Cartaway is notable since it involved the actions of individual market participants, as opposed to cases like Asbestos, where the commission was urged to intervene in a transaction.257 The Cartaway court arguably moved [*219] away from the characterization of the power as "preventative in nature and prospective in orientation" and toward something more akin to a penal law by framing "general deterrence" as a proper consideration when deciding whether to impose sanctions on an individual on public interest grounds.258 i. Scope of the "Public Interest Jurisdiction" The pre-1994 caselaw established crucial boundaries for the public interest power that are still applicable today.259 The OSC first announced that it could exercise its public interest jurisdiction in Cablecasting even if there was no violation of the Act.260 A group of minority shareholders in Cablecasting Ltd. requested a cease-trade order under Section 144 (now Section 127) to prevent the firm from completing a going-private transaction.261 Even though, the Commission refused to issue a cease-trade order, it asserted that it could invoke its public interest jurisdiction in circumstances where there has been no contravention of securities laws, and more specifically, when an "individual with an imagination sufficiently fertile [could] invent an unethical scheme which skirts the words of all published pronouncements [and] may carry out that scheme with impunity."262 However, while the Commission has the ability to offer relief on public-interest grounds in the absence of a violation of the Act, it should refrain from employing "this authority except on facts that justify some relief."263 Although this exceptional regulatory power could be exercised without the need to have a specific breach of the law, it has been reserved for conduct that rises to the level of "abuse" of investors or the capital markets.264 Nine years after Cablecasting, the OSC ruled that the insider bid transaction in the Canadian Tire case was abusive of the capital markets, and therefore, illegal, even if there was no real breach of securities laws.265 Eventually, the take-over bid by CTC Dealer Holdings Ltd. to purchase 49% of the issued and outstanding common shares of Canadian Tire Corporation was found to be, in substance, a purchase of all of the common shares in Canadian Tire [*220] owned by the then-controlling shareholders.266 The deal was designed to avoid triggering a "coattail" clause, which would have permitted non-voting stockholders to participate in the bid.267 The OSC noted that [i]f abusive transactions such as the one in issue here, and this is as grossly abusive a transaction as the Commission has had before it in recent years, are allowed to proceed, confidence in our capital markets will inevitably suffer and individuals will be less willing to place funds in the equity markets. That can only have a deleterious effect on our capital markets . . . .268 Public confidence in capital markets is, therefore, crucial and must be protected by securities regulators acting as gatekeepers. The OSC, for the first time, referred to the "spirit and intent" of the Act to justify the exercise of its public interest jurisdiction in Mithras.269 In this case, respondents took advantage of a take-over bid exemption to carry out tax-motivated "buy backs" of units in certain limited partnerships that had been issued to investors to fund episodes of a television series.270 Under the exemption, respondents were allowed to limit the amount of information to be disclosed under securities laws.271 Notwithstanding the compliance of the take-over bid with the Act, the OSC found the failure to disclose obviously relevant information to offerees in the course of a take-over bid to be run against the "spirit and intent" of the take-over bid provisions of the Act.272 As a result, the take-over bid exemption did not apply to the respondents.273 In Mithras, the OSC noted that the public interest power is designed to be forward looking rather than punitive in nature.274 ii. From a Preventative in Nature and Prospective in Orientation to Deterrence and Punishment The OSC has begun to use its public interest jurisdiction over the last few years in a growing number of instances involving market actors' past behavior and the possibility of imposing sanctions on them.275 In Biovail, the [*221] OSC examined statements made by Biovail Corp. ("Biovail") in news releases after a multi-vehicle accident involving a truck carrying antidepressant drugs manufactured by Biovail.276 Under Section 122, public statements were found to be "misleading or untrue in a material respect."277 However, the OSC eventually found that there had been no violation of the Act since the statements were not made in documents that were "required to be filed or furnished" within the meaning of Section 122(1)(b).278 Moreover, the documents were only posted to the System for Electronic Document Analysis and Retrieval, not "submitted" to the Commission within the meaning of Section 122(1)(a).279 Nevertheless, the OSC chose to exercise its public interest jurisdiction to reprimand the Chief Executive Officer of Biovail, as in its view, the use of such power does not require the proof of an abuse as long as the market conduct engages the animating principles of the Act.280 According to the OSC, there is no reason for the public interest jurisdiction of Section 127 not to apply to cases beyond the scope of Section 122.281 By this, the OSC established the applicability of Section 127 to statements in documents that are not filed or furnished under the Act or are not submitted to the OSC.282 Hence, by allowing itself to investigate any public statement, not simply those that violate Section 122, the OSC appears to have effectively altered the Act, notwithstanding the legislature's refusal to condone such behavior.283 Another case that highlights the broad discretion the OSC has while exercising its public interest jurisdiction is Donald. In this case, Paul Donald, former Vice President of Research In Motion ("RIM"), was accused by the staff of the Commission of purchasing securities of Certicom Corp. ("Certicom") in contravention of the insider trading provisions of the Act.284 The OSC held that Mr. Donald was not in a "special relationship" with Certicom, since, at the time of the purchase, an acquisition of Certicom had not been "proposed" by RIM within the meaning of Section 76(5) of the Act.285 Even though RIM's acquisition of Certicom was a serious possibility . . . RIM had not at that time reached the stage of proposing to make a bid to acquire Certicom securities. We must therefore conclude that Donald did not breach subsection 76(1) of the Act when he purchased Certicom shares in August and September 2008.286 [*222] Despite the fact that the OSC did not find any technical breach of subsection 76(1) of the Act, it concluded that Mr. Donald's purchase of Certicom shares "directly engage[s] the fundamental principles of securities regulation" and that the unusual circumstances of the case warrant a finding that Donald's conduct was against the public interest.287 Again, the OSC was very comfortable in imposing sanctions on Mr. Donald, who obeyed the law as it existed at the time.288 The exercise of the public interest jurisdiction in this scenario shows that the primary concern of the OSC is to prevent conduct that impugns the integrity of Ontario's capital markets, regardless of their legality at the time of their occurrence.289 As noted above, the absence of the violation of the Act will not operate as an obstacle for the OSC to exercise it public interest jurisdiction so long as market participants have (i) deliberately skirted a particular provision of the Act in such a way that they achieve an outcome the Act intended to prevent, (ii) committed a conduct that rises to the level of abuse of investors or the capital markets, (iii) acted in a way that runs against the "spirit and intent" of the take-over bid provisions of the Act, (iv) performed acts that engage the animating principles of the Act, or (v) directly engaged the fundamental principles of securities regulation. V. NO MARKET MANIPULATION UNDER U.S. AND CANADIAN LAW, BUT THE EXERCISE OF THE PUBLIC INTEREST JURISDICTION OF THE OSC WOULD HAVE BEEN APPROPRIATEA. GameStop Frenzy not a Pump-and-Dump Scheme in the U.S. or Canada1. Meme Stock Saga does not exactly fit into any of the Previous SEC Guidance and Federal Court Precedent Individuals who have used social media to perpetrate securities fraud have faced criminal charges in the past.290 In SEC v. Craig, the defendant James Alan Craig created Twitter accounts with names similar, if not identical, to well-known securities research firms Muddy Waters and Citron [*223] Research.291 He shared a decent amount of false tweets, including one claiming that Audience Inc., was under investigation by the Justice Department.292 As a result, Audience Inc.'s shares price dropped sharply, and the volume of shares traded on the day of his tweets was ten times that of the day before.293 A final judgment was rendered against Craig as the SEC was able to prove that he created market disruption and his "fraudulent conduct also caused tremendous intangible harm to the U.S. markets."294 SEC v. McKeown is another example of a successful pump-and-dump lawsuit initiated by the SEC.295 McKeown and her partner Ryan used their website and social media platforms to "pump-and-dump" penny stocks.296 Defendants were able to predict when the price in these stocks would massively increase, and they actually sold when they did.297 The SEC alleged that Defendants committed securities fraud in violation of the SEC Act.298 The SEC prevailed as the court issued a permanent injunction against Defendants and ordered them to pay $ 3.794 million in disgorgement for profits.299 Reddit users clearly "pumped" the GameStop stocks as the stock price rose from $ 20 in early January of 2021 to $ 500 later the same month.300 Nevertheless, unlike Craig and McKeown, the statements made by Reddit users during the meme stock saga were transparent and part of the public domain.301 The Canadian law is to some extent similar to the U.S. law as it requires the proof of a non-bona fide trading and manipulative intent.302 Unlike the defendants in Re Kilimanjaro Capital Ltd, Keith Gill, and other Reddit users did not have a secret control over the issuances and liquidation of the GME shares.303 Investors and outsiders were actually the driving force responsible for the rise in the meme stock value.304 There is no evidence that a GME director or counsel was involved in the meme stock saga.305 The [*224] reddit posts are distinguishable from the press announcements regarding Kilimanjaro's existing partnerships with exiled governments and its intent to purchase some oil and gas properties. Keith Gill and his fans were only discussing the potential of meme stock and its effect on the market as a whole.306 The meme stock saga involves encouragement for risky investments rather than false promises and misrepresentation of facts about GME financials.307 For instance, Keith Gill, a registered securities broker, was transparent while communicating to his fans and he did not use any false social media accounts.308 Mr. Gill made millions of dollars out of this chaotic situation that brought the right crowd together (young inexperienced investors) at the right time (the Coronavirus pandemic).309 Current U.S. and Canadian laws were designed to regulate traditional market participants, not evolving markets in which social media platforms can control market valuations.310 Jordan Belfort, the real "Wolf of Wall Street," found this to be a digital market manipulation that involves a modified version of the pump-and-dump scheme where market participants use innovative ways to manipulate the market.311 He correctly noted that people who will end up losing the most are "the widows and the orphans, or the unprofessionals that keep hearing about it, . . ." and think they are going to become millionaires by joining the shenanigans.312 It worked perfectly for Mr. Gill who won the golden egg when the dust settled. If regulators would want to go after anyone in this context, it would be impractical to go after retail traders who were using social media platforms.313 It could be argued that neither investors nor the trading platforms appear to be doing anything illegal or wrong, but they are taking big risks, and some of them do not even realize it. [*225] 2. Meme Stock Phenomenon does not Directly Amount to a Breach of the Securities Act in Canada In Canada, a breach of the Securities Act in some provinces occurs when any of the following takes place: artificial price, misleading appearance of trading activity, or pump-and-dump scheme.314 i. Not a Strong "Artificial Price" Case Even though trading in GME was a special phenomenon, it does not fit into the artificial price box. One could argue that the market was subject to the influence of Reddit users, brokerage firms, and hedge funds who collectively rendered the operation of the market unfair and controlled to a large number of investors. However, the use of Robinhood app and other similar brokerage applications was still the result of normal-course transactions between buyers and sellers operating at arm's length on the market.315 To some extent, it could be said that the market was operating freely and fairly on the basis of information concerning true market supply and demand. ii. Not a Solid "Misleading Appearance of Trading Activity" Case GME stock trading does not fall within the premises of the "misleading appearance of trading activity" cause of action since the bets placed by retail and institutional investors were part of bona fide trading. There was certainly more than an "appearance of trading activity" as a decent amount of innocent and lucky investors profited substantially from investing in meme stocks while others lost thousands, if not millions of dollars.316 Therefore, GME trading is distinguishable from this specific market manipulation cause of action despite the fact that they both resulted in an artificial stock price to some extent. iii. Not a "Wash Trading" Scenario The meme stock frenzy does not fit within the "wash trade" box because stock buyers and sellers were not the same person. Different market participants were actually engaged in a bidding war where the ultimate ownership of meme stock was constantly changing as millions of actual [*226] transactions were being consummated.317 Hence, a wash trading argument would certainly fail in court. 3. The Meme Stock Saga Was a Good Case for the OSC to Exercise its Public Interest Jurisdiction The OSC had multiple grounds to exercise its public interest jurisdiction amidst the unprecedented market volatility.318 Viewing the previous cases where the OSC exercised its public interest jurisdiction even absent any violation of the Act, many predicted the OSC to step in, but it did not.319 Mr. Gill and other Reddit users could be accused of deliberately skirting a particular provision of the Act in such a way that they achieve an outcome the Act intended to prevent. Brokerage firms would also be on the hook if it were found that their decisions to halt trading were related to hedge fund manager interests.320 The wild swing in the GME and AMC stock price could be traceable to one or more individuals with an imagination sufficiently fertile to invent an unethical scheme which skirted the words of all published pronouncements and carried out that scheme with impunity.321 The actions of the market participants, taken in the aggregate, could be sanctioned as being against the "spirit and intent" of the Act, which would prompt the OSC to exercise its exceptional regulatory power without the need to have a specific breach of the law. Just like in Biovail and Donald, the OSC could have investigated public statements, not simply those that violate Section 122, and imposed sanctions on Reddit users and other market participants to prevent conducts that impugn the integrity of Ontario's capital markets, regardless of their legality at the time of their occurrence.322 4. Regulatory Intervention Would have led to a Clash with the Freedom of Speech There is a fine line between the freedom of speech and digital market manipulation. An investigation of non-fraudulent speeches by the securities regulators could raise First Amendment concerns.323 According to Jacob Frenkel, former senior enforcement lawyer at the SEC, "[a]ny country that [*227] embraces free speech cannot have its securities regulator restricting the right of expression."324 Any content-based governmental regulation of speech will be upheld only if it is necessary to achieve a compelling governmental interest and is narrowly tailored to meet that interest.325 A law is content-based if it applies to certain speech because of the subject discussed or the idea expressed.326 However, even regulations that on the surface do not appear to be content-based may nonetheless be applied or intended to be content-based, and they will typically be strictly scrutinized.327 Reddit users were eventually expressing advice and opinions that could be far beyond the scope of free speech and part of commercial speech subject to restriction on the basis of content. Reddit posts and other social media communication related to meme stock would be entitled to an intermediate level of First Amendment protection.328 Restrictions on commercial speech are upheld when (i) the commercial speech concerns a lawful activity and is neither false nor misleading, (ii) the governmental interest is substantial, (iii) the restriction directly advances the asserted interest, and (iv) the regulation is narrowly tailored to serve that interest.329 The SEC and OSC struggled in determining whether social media comments constituted a lawful activity that is neither false nor misleading.330 Were they in fact true and not misleading? This question is beyond this Note, but it is important to point out that the answer could change as the time goes by and securities regulation frameworks are amended. VI. RECOMMENDATIONS Non-traditional market participants are grabbing the digital investments' steering wheel and the action of the legislature and securities regulators is needed. The U.S. and Canada should be equipped for the future as the gamification of trading is spreading in various ways and young investors are enjoying the idea of making easy money.331 With Reddit, Discord, and other social media platforms, retail investors could be tempted [*228] to take the lead again and recreate a similar hype.332 The public interest jurisdiction has been criticized by some Canadian jurists for being arbitrary and uncertain.333 Viewing the legal infrastructure in the United States, giving the SEC a similar power would undoubtedly face significant opposition from many individuals who contend that it is overbroad and general.334 As mentioned above, the meme stock saga does not perfectly meet any of the grounds that would allow the OSC to exercise its public interest jurisdiction.335 While the regulatory framework in the United States and Canada is not without limitations, it may not be sufficiently robust to effectively address the phenomenon of the meme stock frenzy. The philosophy of the securities laws reduced to its essence is full and fair disclosure of all the important information that an investor could reasonably want in order to make an investment decision.336 Markets should be free of manipulation and protected from people who seek to engage in tactics that arbitrarily drive the prices up and down. As nebulous as the concept of public interest jurisdiction might be, the U.S. and Canadian legal systems are not fully prepared to handle this purportedly hybrid scheme of market manipulation. VII. CONCLUSION The U.S. and Canada should both consider revising the definition of market manipulation to reflect the recent developments and establish legal grounds that will allow them to prevent social media users and brokerage firms to manipulate the market as they did amidst the Coronavirus pandemic. Governments and regulators will have to navigate their way to establish a legal framework that does not impede the freedom of speech, especially when market participants' statements are part of the public domain yet they are mainly aimed at artificially affecting stock market prices. The scienter requirement for market manipulation could also be amended in way that expands its scope to capture additional mental states that are traditionally left out of the definition of market manipulation. First, this Note analyzed the meme stock saga under the U.S. and Canadian legal systems. Second, it explored other grounds of market manipulation under the public interest jurisdiction that could apply in this scenario. Third, it showed that neither legal framework could perfectly apply to regulate this phenomenon. Fourth, [*229] this Note shed light on the different approaches adopted by both legal systems and the obstacles that prevent the implementation of the Canadian legal framework in the U.S. University of Dayton Law Review 2023

  1. Plot the amount of nrc emotion words as a percentage of all the emotion words used each day (aggregate text from articles published on the same day). How does the distribution of emotion words change over time? Can you think of any reason this would be the case?

So this is actually impossible for the data that Im working with. To follow the request as closely as possible, I am aggregating by year and removing the years that fall outside of expected publication dates.

As expected, a drastic influx of NRC words appeared during the years that tik tok become more prevelent and controversial in American media. I am surprised by the decrease in NRC word frequency in the most recent year because there are politicians currently at work trying to actively ban tik tok. I havent been able to keep super up to date, but if I rememeber correctly, there was something on their ballot for potentially banning tik tok in the next several months. I would expect more articles to include NRC because of this, but this could be a result of the distribution of years Ive downloaded. The majority appear to be from the spiked years, so this is likely influencing the plot below and skewing the spike compared to 2023-2024.

# Aggregate text from articles published on the same year
dat2_grouped <- dat2 %>%
  # Remove years 1986 and 1994 because they're not related to today's tik tok
  filter(year != 1986 & year != 1994) %>%  
  na.omit(year) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(agg_text = paste(text, collapse = " "))

# Tokenize the aggregated text
text_words <- dat2_grouped %>% 
  unnest_tokens(output = word,
                input = agg_text,
                token = "words")

# Join with NRC sentiment lexicon
nrc_words_count <- text_words %>% 
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word") %>% 
  inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>%
  count(year, sentiment, sort = TRUE)

# Calculate the percentage of NRC emotion words out of all emotion words used each year
nrc_percentage <- nrc_words_count %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarise(nrc_count = sum(n)) %>%
  left_join(
    dat2_grouped %>% select(year),
    by = "year"
  ) %>%
  mutate(total_count = sum(nrc_count)) %>%
  mutate(percentage = (nrc_count / total_count) * 100)

# Plot the distribution of NRC emotion word percentage over time
ggplot(nrc_percentage, aes(x = year, y = percentage)) +
  geom_line(col = 'skyblue',
            size = 3) +
  labs(title = "Percentage of NRC Emotion Words Over Years",
       subtitle = "Topic: Tik Tok Ban",
       x = "Year",
       y = "Percentage of NRC Emotion Words") +
  theme_classic() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5,
                              size = 20),
    
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5,
                              size = 15)
  )
